messages.reasoning_content:
I see that `foldOrOfEquivalentOverflowChecks` is called, but only when `!IsLogical` (line 3196). The issue is that the test case uses a regular `or` instruction, not a logical or. Let me check what `IsLogical` means.

Looking at the test case:
```llvm
define i1 @test(i64 %a, i64 %b){
  %s = add i64 %a, %b
  %cond_a = icmp ult i64 %s, %a
  %cond_b = icmp ult i64 %s, %b
  %cond = or i1 %cond_a, %cond_b
  ret i1 %cond
}
```

This is a regular `or` instruction on i1 values, not a logical or. Let me check how `IsLogical` is determined.

But wait, I need to look more carefully at the `foldOrOfEquivalentOverflowChecks` function. Looking at line 1167-1175:
```cpp
// Check if LHS1 and RHS1 are the two addends (in any order)
bool LHS1isA = (LHS1 == A);
bool LHS1isB = (LHS1 == B);
bool RHS1isA = (RHS1 == A);
bool RHS1isB = (RHS1 == B);

// We need LHS1 and RHS1 to be different addends
if (!((LHS1isA && RHS1isB) || (LHS1isB && RHS1isA)))
  return nullptr;
```

The problem here is that the comparison `LHS1 == A` compares `Value*` pointers. This only works if the values are literally the same instruction/value object. But in the test case:
```llvm
%s = add i64 %a, %b


%cond_a = icmp ult i64 %s, %a
%cond_b = icmp ult i64 %s, %b
```

